"{\"uid\": \"news.sky.com-story-imane-khelif-algerian-boxer-at-centre-of-gender-row-wins-gold-to-become-olympic-champion-13194173\", \"text\": \"The fighter comfortably overcame her Chinese rival and appeared unfazed by the controversy that has swirled around her participation.  Saturday 10 August 2024 00:49, UK  The Algerian boxer at the centre of a gender row at the Paris games has been crowned Olympic champion.  Imane Khelif comfortably beat China's Yang Liu by unanimous decision to win gold in the women's welterweight final.  She won each of the three rounds on the judges' scorecards and jumped into the arms of her trainer when the decision was announced. He carried the 25-year-old round the arena on his shoulders in celebration.  Olympics 2024 LIVE! News, updates and latest results from Paris  \\\"For eight years, this has been my dream, and I am now the Olympic champion and gold medalist,\\\" Khelif said through an interpreter.  Asked about the row, she told reporters: \\\"That also gives my success a special taste because of those attacks.\\\"  \\\"I am fully qualified to take part in this competition,\\\" she added. \\\"I am a woman like any other woman. I was born as a woman, I live as a woman, and I am qualified.\\\"  Khelif had been under intense scrutiny after a previous fighterquit after 46 seconds, saying it was to protect her health as the Algerian's punches were so strong.  Khelif had said winning gold would be the\\\"best response\\\" to her critics.  Some argued she should not have been allowed to compete due to concerns she might have elevated testosterone that can lead to extra strength and muscle - potentially endangering her opponent.  Khelif and a Taiwanese boxer were banned from the world championships last year, with the International Boxing Association (IBA) saying they failed gender eligibility tests.  Please use Chrome browser for a more accessible video player    However, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) said the decision was \\\"sudden and arbitrary\\\" and the tests were majorly flawed.  It has banned the IBA over governance issues, alleged corruption and ties to Russia.  \\ud83d\\udc49Click to subscribe to the Sky News Daily wherever you get your podcasts\\ud83d\\udc48  IOC spokesperson Mark Adams said all the boxers in Paris met eligibility criteria - with gender and age \\\"based on their passport\\\".  He said Khelif and Taiwan's Lin Yu-ting had been competing in women's competition for many years and the Algerian also appeared at the Tokyo games.  Read more from Sky News:Passenger plane carrying 61 people crashes in BrazilRapper Travis Scott arrested in Paris  Keep up with all the latest news from the UK and around the world by following Sky News  Be the first to getBreaking News  Install the Sky News app for free  The debate over the boxers has seen renewed discussion over athletes who may have differences in sexual development (DSD).  DSD covers a group of conditions involving genes, hormones and reproductive organs developing differently than expected.  However, it is not known whether Khelif and Yu-ting - who fights in her own final on Saturday - have such variations.\"}"